review the accounting entry during approval of the JRequire the Accounting Office to remind the accounting personnel tasked with the preparation of Journal Entry Vouchers to use the proper account title appropriate to the transaction, properly supported by appropriate documents and to personnel assigned to review the accounting entry during approval of the JEV.
Require the GSO to maintain stock cards and present to the audit team when needed; and
Undertake regular reconciliation of accounting and GSO records and promptly adjust any discrepancies noted to ensure complete and reliable Inventory account balances at any given reporting period.

Recommendation/s:
We reiterated the prior year’s recommendation to the management to undertake the following:
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to prepare and periodically update the schedule of items composing the PPE accounts enumerated in Tables 2 and 3, together with pertinent data such as the acquisition cost, acquisition date and estimated useful life. After which, apply the guidelines prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004 dated May 31, 2022 relative to the increase of capitalization threshold for PPE and reclassify items previously recognized PPE items with cost below the 50K threshold;
Require the accountant to maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledger/s of a particular general ledger and present to the audit team when needed;
Require the GSO to maintain property cards;
Undertake regular reconciliation of accounting and GSO records and promptly adjust any discrepancies noted to ensure complete and reliable PPE account balances at any given reporting period;
Submit the lacking RPCPPEs using the prescribed format and thereafter submit altogether the report of physical count conducted; and
Create an inventory committee and conduct the one- time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU following the guidelines and procedures in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, to eliminate unreconciled and unidentified balances.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
To require the Accounting Office, Municipal Engineering Office, the GSO and the Inventory Committee to coordinate in assessing the value of the road lot component and for its subsequent recording in the books of account;
Require the Engineering Office and the GSO to furnish the audit team a copy of the road map;
Require the GSO to keep and maintain Property Card for Local Road Network and to use the prescribed format of the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;
Require the Accounting Office to maintain the Local Road Network Ledger Card;
Require the Accounting Office to observe the non-provision of residual value in the computation of depreciation expense of the depreciable component of the Road Network account, reflect the actual date of completion of the project in the lapsing schedule and to make the necessary adjustment on the accounts affected by the erroneous computation of depreciation expense as of December 31, 2024; and
Instruct the accounting Office to make appropriate disclosure of the road network in the Notes to FS following the presentation prescribed by the existing circular.

Recommendation/s:
We reiterated our recommendation to the Local Chief Executive to require the Accounting Office to undertake the following:
Continue conducting confirmation of the dormant payable account balances with the identified suppliers/individuals to establish the existence of liability and require pertinent documents to support their claim for the processing of payments;
Thoroughly review and analyze the accounts payable balances and supporting documentation to identify any discrepancies and irregularities, effect necessary adjustments and consider reverting the same to the un-appropriated surplus, if claims cannot be established;
Require the Inspectorate Team to strictly indicate the date of inspection in the AIR;
Implement appropriate measures to ensure that all future accounts payable transactions are properly supported by a valid documentation; and
Recognize liability only to claims with complete supporting documents in order to sufficiently establish the existence and valuation of the obligations as of reporting period in accordance with IPSAS 1 and Section 4(s), Volume I of the NGAS Manual.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended to the management to direct the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Undertake a thorough review and analysis of the details of the mandatory Inter-Agency accounts and submit to the audit team the reconciliation of amounts withheld still existing as of December 31, 2024;
Facilitate reconciliation with the concerned government agencies if necessary;
Address the bottlenecks in the delay of submission of reports to the identified government agencies to avoid recurrence in the future; and
If warranted, cause immediate remittance to various government agencies the amount due for the current and past due payables not yet remitted.

We reiterated our recommendations to the Head of the Agency to require the Accounting Office to:
Exhaust all means necessary to obtain the needed reports, records and documents to identify the variances from the period 2013 and below and make the adjusting entries, as warranted;
Reconcile the items recorded in the accounts in CY 2014 and above and effect the necessary adjustments;
Submit to the Office of the Auditor the reconciliation papers and journal entry voucher for the adjustments, for audit and verification; and
Henceforth, ensure due diligence in the recording of reciprocal accounts and conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to timely address any variances.

We recommended that the management:
Instruct the accountable officer to immediately render liquidation and make immediate refund of the unliquidated and excess cash advances;
Ensure proper planning of activities to avoid accumulation of needed cash advance. 
Require a certification from the Accountant for every cash advance, that the previous grant to the AO have been fully liquidated to control the grant and liquidation of cash advances.
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to monitor the granted cash advances and immediately demand liquidation from concerned AO after completion of the activities;
Ensure that cash advances granted to SDOs are liquidated in full at year end.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to require the Accounting Office to undertake the following: 
Commence sending out written confirmations to the identified suppliers/individuals with payable amounts aging 2 to 10 years in order to establish the existence of liability and require pertinent documents to support their claim for the processing of payments, otherwise, request a certification of no unpaid obligations from the suppliers/individuals to support reversal from the books of accounts;
Prepare adjusting entry to correct the non- reversal of liabilities for paid motor vehicle, including the accumulated depreciation previously recognized; 
Implement appropriate measures to ensure that all future accounts payable transactions are properly supported by a valid documentations and proof of receipt of goods and services as of reporting date; and
Recognize liability only for claims with complete supporting documents in order to sufficiently establish the existence and valuation of the obligations as of reporting period in accordance with IPSAS 1 and Section 4(s), Volume I of the NGAS Manual.

We recommended the management to:
Submit an explanation and justification on the following:
Necessity to conduct the CY 2024 budget review outside the LGU’s jurisdiction or outside the Region 10;
Non adoption of the proper mode of procurement of hotel accommodation during travels;
Delay in the refund of excess cash advance for travel made to Bacolod;
Necessity of all the members of the Sangguniang Bayan to travel to Manila for above-mentioned purpose; and
Incurrence of 50kg baggage allowance.
Submit the following noted lacking documents to support the propriety and validity of the transactions:
LGU’s approved CapDev Agenda;
Certificate of Appearance of 33 travelling officials for November 14.16-17, 2023;
Documents to support the best practices identified were drawn from the list of publicly recognized good practices;
Completion report or action plan as a result of the conducted benchmarking activity;
Receipts evidencing payment of the taxi fare totaling P16,500 for travel to Manila on December 5-7, 2023;
Require refund of the amount intended for the accommodation as part of the full DTE granted to 11 officials despite provision of accommodation;
Avoid the conduct of out-of-office meetings or travels outside the official station that are unnecessary and consider conducting similar activities with the Region 10;
For the future benchmarking activities, limit the number of participants and consider the employee’s position/function, ability to manage the adoption of the best practices, and ability to impart knowledge acquired or conduct of the re-echo seminar;
Ensure compliance with the requirements of DBM-DILG Joint Circular prior and after the conduct of travel of benchmarking/lakbay-aral;
The accountable Officer shall liquidate within one (10 calendar month after the return to the official station of the official/employee for local travel; and
Require the BAC to strictly comply with the required mode of procurement of competitive public bidding for the procurement with an approved budget of more than P100,000.00.  For procurement pf airline tickets, consider the applicability of the provision under Section 53.14 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184.

