We recommended the management to:

a.	Observe the prescribed minimum employees’ monthly net take home pay of P5,000.00 under the GAA; 
b.	Stop immediately the practice of including the loan amortizations due to private lending institutions as deductions from the payroll if it reduces the employee’s monthly net take home pay to an amount below what is prescribed; 
c.	Advise the affected employees to pay directly to the rural banks for any deficiency in the deducted loan amortizations; and 
d.	Limit the accommodation of loan deduction for private lending institutions and incorporate in the MOA the prescribed net take home pay under the GAA, to clearly establish the LGUs responsibility for the deductions.

We recommended the following: 
Prepare adjusting entry by debiting the account “Due from NGOs/POs” and crediting the account “Due to Other NGAs” in the amount of P500,000.00;
Submit financial reports together with all the supporting documents in the utilization of the said funds;
Submit inspection report and Certificate of Project completion issued by the Municipality of Sumilao; and,
Submit Official Receipt issued by the LGU of Sumilao as acknowledgment of the refund of P500,000.00.

We recommended the management to strengthen their internal control system from procurement, receipt, distribution and monitoring of drugs, medicines and medical supplies by doing considering the following, among others:

a.	Instruct the Municipal Rural Health Officer to inform the LCE and Municipal Accounting Office on every receipt of drugs and medicines from other sources;
b.	Accountant should record such receipts from other sources as debit to Inventories and credit to Grants and Donations In Kind;
c.	At the end of each month, the RHU should submit reports on actual consumption of drugs, medicines and medical supplies in the Municipal Accounting Office;
d.	Accountant must base the recording of expense on actual consumption of drugs and medicines.
e.	Stock Cards must be maintained by the GSO for every item in stock of the drugs, medicines and medical supplies.
f.	At year end, the GSO must report the result of their physical count of drugs, medicines and medical supplies which shall be incorporated in the annual Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI).

We reiterated our recommendation to management to undertake the following:
Strictly require from the person responsible, the BRS as of December 31, 2012 identifying all reconciling items to enable proper adjustments in the LGU’s books;
Require the Municipal Accountant to adjust all identified reconciling items in the BRS as of December 31, 2019 duly supported with necessary documents. The Municipal Accounting Office shall, in the subsequent periods,  promptly adjust the accounting records as soon as the reconciling items are verified and identified;
Require immediate refund from the check signatories the P10,000.00 bank charges for dis-honored check issued by the LGU; 
The Municipal Accountant shall make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the erroneous adjustments made to the TF Regular account; and
Instruct the Municipal Treasurers Office to locate and secure the DVs and its supporting documents of the unrecorded check issuances appearing in the BRS to avoid suspension in audit and to enable their recording in the books of accounts, then immediately submit them to COA for appropriate action.

We strongly recommended the following:
a) The Inventory Committee conduct complete physical inventory of all PPEs owned by the Municipality.  To facilitate the inventory taking, the GSO may require each office to conduct physical count of PPEs under their custody and prepare an inventory report that is complete in all particulars, such as, item description, model, serial number and property numbers, acquisition costs and dates, for submission to the Inventory Committee who in turn will validate the submitted inventory reports and come up with the consolidated RPCPPE;
b) The Accountant and GSO analyze the discrepancies noted in the balances of PPE accounts per physical count, subsidiary ledger and even in the lapsing schedule to (i) effect the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts, (ii) prepare the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards with complete details, and (iii) adjust the balances of accumulated depreciation for all PPE accounts to present fairly the PPE balances in the financial statements;
c) The Management to create a committee to conduct an appraisal of all existing PPEs without cost to determine the fair value and the estimated remaining useful life for proper valuation of property in accordance with PPSAS 17;
d) To submit a complete inventory Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) not later than June 30, 2018 and January 31 of the succeeding years.

